        "**(Question 5):** What is the method of least squares in linear regression?"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "KgEuAL_Zy3-t"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "**Answer:**\n",
        "\n",
        "The method of least squares is a mathematical approach used to find the best-fitting line in linear regression.\n",
        " It minimizes the sum of the squared differences between the observed values and the predicted values (residuals).\n",
        " This ensures that the line is as close as possible to the data points."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "EFwEu4hUy-0_"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "**(Question 6):** What is Logistic Regression?\n",
        " How does it differ from Linear Regression?"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "2HPzWvZpzHjl"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "**Answer:**\n",
        "\n",
        "Logistic Regression is a statistical method used for binary classification problems, where the dependent variable is categorical (e.g., yes/no, 0/1). It predicts the probability of an event occurring using a logistic function (sigmoid curve).\n",
        "\n",
        "Difference:\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "*   Linear Regression predicts continuous values, while Logistic Regression\n",
        "predicts probabilities for categorical outcomes.\n",
        "*   Logistic Regression uses a sigmoid function, whereas Linear Regression uses a straight line\n",
        "\n",
        "\n"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "D_cZozt1zO-1"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "**(Question 7):** Name and briefly describe three common evaluation metrics for regression models."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "QqZN7b9nznYt"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "**Answer:**  \n",
        "\n",
        "Three common evaluation metrics for regression models.\n",
        "\n",
        "*   Mean Absolute Error (MAE): Measures the average magnitude of errors between predicted and actual values.\n",
        "*   Mean Squared Error (MSE): Calculates the average of squared differences between predicted and actual values, penalizing larger errors more heavily.\n",
        "*   R-squared (Coefficient of Determination): Indicates the proportion of variance in the dependent variable explained by the independent variable(s)."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "AdaJ4Iykz3t9"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "**(Question 8):** What is the purpose of the R-squared metric in regression analysis?"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "g8l8NksO0Sat"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "**Answer:**\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "R-squared measures the proportion of the variance in the dependent variable that is explained by the independent variable(s) in the model.\n",
        " It indicates how well the regression model fits the data, with values closer to 1 representing a better fit."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "diMl2iPo0cBd"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "**(Question 9):** Write Python code to fit a simple linear regression model using scikit-learn and print the slope and intercept."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "Qdciuvlr0hdE"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression\n",
        "import numpy as np\n",
        "\n",
        "X = np.array([[1], [2], [3], [4], [5]])\n",
        "y = np.array([2, 4, 6, 8, 10])\n",
        "\n",
        "model = LinearRegression()\n",
        "model.fit(X, y)\n",
        "\n",
        "print(\"Slope (β₁):\", model.coef_[0])\n",
        "print(\"Intercept (β₀):\", model.intercept_)"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"
        },
        "id": "KAUKSC880xFF",
        "outputId": "5838f7c3-2092-4654-d7e5-10b914f44fd6"
      },
      "execution_count": 1,
      "outputs": [
        {
          "output_type": "stream",
          "name": "stdout",
          "text": [
            "Slope (β₁): 2.0\n",
            "Intercept (β₀): 0.0\n"
          ]
        }
      ]
